===Etymology 4===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|„āÄ„Āį„āČ|alt=Ťćä}}

Appears in the {{w|Heian period}},<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> apparently as a shift from ''ubara''.  Used in ''{{w|The Tales of Ise}}'' dating to the early 900s CE.<ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>

Considering the earlier free alternation between ''ubara'' and ''umara'', suggesting a possible {{w|Prenasalized consonant|prenasalized}} pronunciation such as *{{IPAchar|/umbara/}}, this ''mubara'' may have arisen from an alternative spelling to clarify nasalization.  Old Japanese [[orthography]] had no unambiguous means of specifying the nasal [[coda]] [[consonant]] {{ja-r|„āď}}, using {{ja-r|„āÄ}} instead.  In fact, the modern kana {{ja-r|„āď}} developed from a [[hentaigana]] form of {{ja-r|„āÄ}}.

[[supersede|Superseded]] by ''ibara'' above.

